Reference-contexts: In learning classifier systems research the problem of how to partition efficiently the state space has been there from the very beginning (see for example Holland 1986; Riolo, 1987; 1989). It has been suggested that the most efficient way to partition the state space is by default hierarchies <ref> (Holland, Holyoak, Nisbett & Thagard, 1986) </ref>. A default hierarchy is a multilevel structure composed of rules (classifiers) with different degree of generality. General rules cover broad set of states, while particular rules can respond to very specific states in which the general rules are wrong.
